HashTableEntry.Value: DIRECTIONS: --- From North Canberra – Travel to Tidbinbilla Nature Reserve via Cotter Road and Paddy’s River Road - approx. 40-50 minutes. --- From South Canberra – Travel to Tidbinbilla Nature Reserve via Point Hut Road and Tidbinbilla Road – approx 25-35 mins. --- ENTRY TO TNR: --- Park in the Carpark and go into the Visitor Information Centre to collect an entry ticket. Rushcutters Bay, Sydney, New South Wales. Come and experience running/walking amongst the art deco buildings in Potts Point, the historical buildings in Elizabeth Bay and around the picturesque bays of Sydney Harbour. Location: Rushcutters Bay Park Assembly: Northern end of Park, at bottom of Holdsworth Ave, near Rushcutters Bay Tennis Centre. Map: Rushcutters Bay (1:7,500) 5metre contours Courses: 1.8km kids course within the park, 2km, 4km, and 6km line Start times: 2-3pm Cost: $10, kids free. SI hire $4 Course closure: 4pm Toilets & water available
Limited parking in surrounding streets - no parking available in the park itself. Consider public transport as an option. By bus (324, 325) it is a 300m walk (4 mins) to assembly area from the bus stop at Bayswater Rd after Waratah St. Or take 311 from Central or Kings Cross stations, alight at Holdsworth Ave stop and walk 100m to assembly area. Alternatively you can travel by train (T4 to Bondi Junction). The assembly area is equidistant from Kings Cross and Edgecliff Stations.
Runners, joggers & walkers all welcome. Beginners are always welcome at our events, and there are always club members on hand to provide some basic coaching. You can go by yourself or as part of a group.

The camp is aimed at allowing juniors to enjoy the squad environment to encourage the social element of orienteering, as well as providing juniors with the fundamental skills required to enjoy the sport of orienteering. For those who will be competing at the Australian Schools Orienteering champs, the camp has the additional focus of preparing the team for the unique challenges of the carnival technically, mentally and physically.
The camp is intended for anyone aged 12-20 who is interested in orienteering as a sport. Orienteers who are older than 20 years old but would like to assist in the camp are welcome to attend as well.
Cost approximately $100-160 per child.

Probably the most beautiful bit of forest on an orienteering map in Victoria, with the lovely Werribee River bisecting the map. It is an unusual orienteering challenge. Subtle spur gully will require accurate compass work, but large fallen trees and areas of thicker vegetation make travelling in a straight line difficult.
Head north for 13 km from the Ballan exit on the Western Freeway to the former Mineral Springs Hotel. Turn right into the Spargo Blakeville Road and continue for 1.4 km to McGees Road. Turn right and follow McGees Road for 2.7 km to Carrolls Track. Turn right again and continue for 500 metres to the assembly area. Do not try to come in on Carrolls Track from the west unless you have a serious 4WD and intend to use it.
Long hard, short hard and moderate courses on offer. The forest is sometimes slow, and courses will be a bit longer than they seem. The long hard course will cross the knee deep Werribee River. Other minor creeks are also flowing. Expect to get wet feet!
Pre-enter please to help with map numbers and pay on the day.

Meet at Faulkner Park Playground. Park at the end of Waratah Ave, Graceville. Arrive around 6.10pm for registration and instructions then a 6.30pm mass start.

All ages and fitness levels catered for. Compete individually or participate in a group. Children under 14 must be accompanied by an adult. Bring a small torch or head lamp. Full instructions given.
Detailed results will be available via the links provided on this page.
$5 per person or $12 per family. Courses close at 7.30pm.
